#compdef html-tool
# ============================================================================
# html-tool - extract tags / attribs / comments / CSS-
#              selected nodes from HTML on stdin
#              (Go, no explicit LICENSE)
#
# Author : Tom Hudson (tomnomnom)
# Upstream: https://github.com/tomnomnom/hacks/tree/master/html-tool
#
# `html-tool` reads a list of URLs or filenames from
# stdin and applies a per-line HTML extraction mode to
# each one. The output stream is one extracted value per
# line - suitable for piping into the rest of a security
# / data-scraping pipeline. It is part of Tom Hudson's
# `hacks` repo, which is a collection of small Unix-pipe-
# friendly Go binaries used heavily across the bug-bounty
# + offensive-security communities (alongside assetfinder,
# anti-burl, fff, gron, qsreplace, waybackurls, and
# similar).
#
# Usage:
#   <urls-or-files> | html-tool <mode> [<args>]
#
# Modes:
#   tags <tag-names>       - extract text inside named
#                            tags (e.g. `tags title a strong`)
#   attribs <attrib-names> - extract attribute values
#                            (e.g. `attribs src href`)
#   comments               - extract HTML comment nodes
#                            (`<!-- ... -->`)
#   query <css-selector>   - extract first-child text of
#                            elements matching the CSS
#                            selector (via the upstream
#                            ericchiang/css cascadia-
#                            style selector engine)
#
# Examples (from upstream README):
#   cat urls.txt | html-tool tags title a strong
#   find . -type f -name "*.html" | html-tool attribs src href
#   cat urls.txt | html-tool comments
#   cat urls.txt | html-tool query "div.main h2"
#
# The x/net/html lane is built on `golang.org/x/net
# v0.0.0-20220722155237-a158d28d115b` (declared verbatim
# at upstream html-tool/go.mod HEAD as a direct dep,
# imported as `golang.org/x/net/html`), the canonical Go
# HTML5 parser by the Go core team in the
# `golang.org/x/net` subrepository - github.com/golang/
# net, 1500+ stars. The `html` subpackage is the Go
# core team's WHATWG-spec-compliant HTML5 tokenizer +
# tree builder, intentionally located in the
# `golang.org/x/net` namespace (alongside http2, idna,
# webdav, websocket, and proxy) to keep the std-lib's
# `net/http` core lean while still providing the spec-
# accurate parser to the broader ecosystem.
#
# The two main entry points are:
#   html.Parse(io.Reader) -> *html.Node
#     - constructs a full tree-builder DOM
#   html.NewTokenizer(io.Reader) -> *html.Tokenizer
#     - streaming token-by-token reader for tools that
#       don't need a full DOM (lower memory)
#
# html-tool uses both styles - the `comments`, `attribs`,
# and `tags` modes use the streaming `Tokenizer` (because
# they only care about individual tokens, not tree
# structure), while the `query` mode uses the full
# `html.Parse` + ericchiang/css selector engine on the
# constructed DOM (because CSS selectors need parent /
# sibling traversal).
#
# Both the streaming Tokenizer + tree-builder Parse follow
# the WHATWG spec's tokenizer state machine + insertion
# mode rules byte-for-byte, so the parsed DOM matches what
# a browser would construct from the same input.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 242 :: HTML5 parsing (WHATWG-spec-compliant DOM
#              construction + CSS selectors)
# Round 1425 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 242
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : servo/html5ever (+ scraper) [R1424 _docrawl]
#   Go      : golang.org/x/net/html       [R1425 THIS FILE]
#   TS/Node : inikulin/parse5             [R1426 closing]
#
# golang.org/x/net/html is structurally interesting in
# this axis because of its *core-team-maintained subrepo*
# governance pattern. Unlike the Rust slot
# (servo/html5ever, extracted from Mozilla's Servo browser
# engine) and the Node slot (inikulin/parse5, an
# independent third-party project later adopted by
# cheerio + jsdom), the Go slot is maintained directly by
# the Go core team in the same `golang.org/x/*` namespace
# as the rest of the experimental + ecosystem-adjacent
# packages.
#
# The split rationale:
#   - core std-lib `net/http` stays minimal (raw HTTP
#     protocol, no markup parsing)
#   - `golang.org/x/net/html` provides the WHATWG-spec
#     HTML5 parser when applications need it
#   - the `golang.org/x/*` namespace is governed under
#     the same review process as std-lib but explicitly
#     marked as "may change in incompatible ways" -
#     allowing the parser to evolve with WHATWG spec
#     drift without breaking std-lib compat guarantees
#
# This structural choice produces a strong network effect:
# every Go-based scraping / SEO tool / link extractor /
# OpenGraph harvester depends on `golang.org/x/net/html`,
# directly or transitively through `goquery` (which is
# itself a wrapper around `x/net/html` + cascadia CSS
# selectors). When tomnomnom built html-tool he picked
# `golang.org/x/net/html` directly + `ericchiang/css`
# for selectors (rather than the heavier goquery facade)
# because of html-tool's pipe-friendly minimalism story.
#
# Cross-language interop happens at the DOM-structure
# level (same WHATWG insertion mode rules produce
# structurally identical trees) but the in-memory
# representation differs per lane:
#   - scraper / html5ever: `ego_tree::Tree<Node>` with
#     arena-allocated nodes
#   - golang.org/x/net/html: `*html.Node` with parent /
#     child / sibling pointer doubly-linked tree
#   - parse5: JSON-shaped JS object tree with parentNode
#     / childNodes / attrs fields
# ============================================================================

_html-tool() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args
    local curcontext="$curcontext" ret=1

    _arguments -C \
        '1: :_html_tool_modes' \
        '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

    case $state in
        args)
            case $words[1] in
                tags|attribs)
                    _arguments \
                        '*:HTML tag or attribute name:'
                    ;;
                query)
                    _arguments \
                        '1:CSS selector:'
                    ;;
                comments)
                    # no extra args
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_html_tool_modes() {
    local -a modes
    modes=(
        'tags:extract text contained in named tags'
        'attribs:extract values of named attributes'
        'comments:extract HTML comment nodes'
        'query:extract first-child text of CSS-selected elements'
    )
    _describe -t modes 'html-tool mode' modes
}

_html-tool "$@"
